4. URL and Data Encoding Standards

Encoding ensures that data remains intact during transmission across different systems and protocols.

Percent (URL) Encoding

Percent encoding is used to represent 8-bit characters that have reserved meanings in URLs.

Character	Encoding	Character	Encoding
null	%00	.	%2E
space	%20	?	%3F
+	%2B	"	%22
%	%25	'	%27
/	%2F	<	%3C
\	%5C	>	%3E

Other Common Formats

* Base64 Encoding: Frequently used for encoding binary data (such as Windows portable executable headers) within email bodies using MIME. Notably, the ASCII "MZ" header appears as "TV" in Base64.
* Unicode: A format commonly extracted from executable files using tools like "Strings."
* UTF-8/ASCII: The standard character set allowed for unreserved characters (a-z, A-Z, 0-9) within URLs.
